# 69_proj_new_doc_smoke — sixth verb on the proj headless-verb
# singleton (s293 m4). Opens a NEW arc beyond m5b — the proj surface
# now extends one cardinality level inward, from project-lifecycle
# verbs (the m5b five: save/save_as/close/load/new) to in-project
# document-lifecycle verbs. `new_doc` is the first verb on that arc.
#
# Tier 4 row remains at 1/~4-5: same singleton, sixth verb; no tick.
# Surface widening: proj verb count 5 → 6. Query count unchanged.
#
# ── What this smoke exercises ─────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Unlike smoke 48 (proj new), THIS smoke runs the verb body from
# Scripter context. new_doc declares its mask as
# ctx::Scripter | ctx::TestRunner — sibling to save's mask, NOT to
# save_as / close / load / new. The architectural reason: new_doc
# ADDS a document to the existing project rather than destroying the
# project as a whole. The script's result surface (project, output
# buffer, host window) is untouched; only the active doc index
# moves. That's not surface-erasing mutation — it's the same class
# of mutation any doc-affecting verb (objects.add, palettes.swatch,
# etc.) performs.
#
# Three call-shapes exercised below:
#
#   - Happy path: `proj new_doc 500 500` — two positive integers,
#     valid project state. Expected trace: `ok`. Side effect: a
#     fresh blank document of pixel size 500x500 lands in the
#     project's documents list, becomes the active doc, panels
#     refresh. No disk I/O (new_doc does NOT auto-save; the GUI
#     dialog callback does, but the script verb leaves persistence
#     to an explicit proj.save call).
#
#   - Argument-shape refusals: `proj new_doc` (zero args),
#     `proj new_doc 100` (one arg), `proj new_doc 100 200 300`
#     (three args). All three refuse at the Scriptable's
#     args.size() != 2 check with "expected exactly two arguments
#     (width and height in pixels)". Three different shapes, three
#     identical structured refusals.
#
#   - Value refusals: `proj new_doc 0 100` (zero), `proj new_doc
#     -50 100` (negative), `proj new_doc "wide" 100` (string).
#     All three refuse at the `w <= 0 || h <= 0` check with "width
#     and height must be positive integers". The string case
#     reaches arg_as_int which returns 0 for non-Int/non-Double
#     kinds, falling through to the same refusal — uniform error
#     voice covers both wrong-kind and wrong-range cases.
#
# What this smoke CAN assert from Scripter:
#
#   - The project's `has_path` is unchanged after each call. The
#     verb body adds an in-memory doc; it does not touch the
#     project's disk path. `proj has_path` before and after each
#     call is the assertable observable for "project surface
#     preserved" — same shape smoke 48 uses for "project not
#     destroyed."
#
#   - The happy-path call lands `ok` on the trace. Operator-visual
#     in the trace; not an `assert` since the DSL's assert is
#     equality-only on query results.
#
# What this smoke CANNOT assert from Scripter today:
#
#   - The new document's canvas dimensions. No `inspector` or
#     `proj` query exposes the active doc's canvas width/height to
#     the script today (inspector's properties are path-safety
#     diagnostics; proj's are path / has_path / dirty). The 500x500
#     contract is operator-visual: read the inspector panel after
#     the run and confirm the Size section reads 500×500 px. A
#     future inspector query for canvas dims would lift this to an
#     assertable observable.
#
#   - The document count growing by one. No `proj.doc_count` query
#     exists today. The operator-visual confirmation is "a new tab
#     appeared in the DocTabBar at the top of the canvas, and the
#     LOG_INFO line `script_new_doc: added 'Untitled.svg' to
#     project (500x500)` appears in the curvz.log."
#
#   - The active_doc_index moving to point at the new doc. Same
#     reason — no query for it. Operator-visual: the canvas now
#     shows the new blank doc, not whatever was active before.
#
# ── Caller context ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Runs through ScripterWindow's listener, m_context =
# RunContext::Scripter. new_doc declares its mask as
# ctx::Scripter | ctx::TestRunner, so the dispatcher's
# context_allows check returns true for invokes from this caller —
# the verb body runs.
#
# Seventh consumer of Scriptable::context_mask() in the codebase
# (Inspector + proj.save + proj.save_as + proj.close + proj.load +
# proj.new + proj.new_doc). Registry-promotion clock at 7/n; STILL
# HELD by design (see ProjScriptable.hpp's context_mask block).
# The catalogue now reads: two verbs at Scripter | TestRunner
# (save, new_doc) and four verbs at TestRunner-only (save_as,
# close, load, new). Two distinct mask shapes is a more interesting
# catalogue than the previous 1+4 uniformity, but the cluster
# boundary tracks the surface-preservation rule cleanly and no
# typo bug has bitten — promotion still held.
#
# ── Test isolation ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Mutates the project state — adds a doc. Repeatable but each run
# accumulates one more Untitled[N].svg in the project's documents
# list (the unique-suffix loop ensures no filename collision). To
# clean up: undo isn't an option (doc-add isn't undoable today;
# backlog), so either close the project without saving (the
# in-memory adds dissolve) or manually delete the doc tabs via the
# UI's tab close button.
#
# No disk I/O — the new doc lives in memory until the script (or
# the user) issues an explicit save.

#[sub] === Phase 1: project state precondition ===

#[sub] Get the project's current directory path. Operator-visual:
#[sub] this should be the .curvz directory Scott has open right now.
#[sub] The has_path assertion below confirms the precondition for
#[sub] the post-call sanity checks (path unchanged through every
#[sub] new_doc call) — if has_path is false here, the sanity checks
#[sub] are meaningless because there's no path to be unchanged.
#[sub]
#[sub] Unlike new — where has_path == false would be a legitimate
#[sub] caller state (no project loaded, ready to create one) —
#[sub] new_doc REQUIRES a loaded project (the NoProject refusal
#[sub] branch). The smoke runs from a loaded-project state so the
#[sub] happy path is reachable.

get proj path

assert proj has_path == true

#[sub] === Phase 2: happy path — 500x500 ===

#[sub] Call new_doc with two valid positive integers. Expected
#[sub] trace line:
#[sub]
#[sub]   ok
#[sub]
#[sub] Side effects (operator-visual):
#[sub]   - A new tab labelled "Untitled.svg" (or "Untitled2.svg" /
#[sub]     "Untitled3.svg" / ... if previous runs left Untitled tabs
#[sub]     behind) appears in DocTabBar.
#[sub]   - The canvas switches to show the new blank doc.
#[sub]   - The inspector's Size section reads 500 × 500 px.
#[sub]   - curvz.log shows: `script_new_doc: added '<filename>' to
#[sub]     project (500x500)`.

proj new_doc 500 500

#[sub] === Phase 3: post-happy-path sanity ===

#[sub] After the new_doc call, the project's directory is unchanged.
#[sub] The add was in-memory only (no auto-save); the project's
#[sub] saved path is whatever it was before. Same structural
#[sub] property smoke 48 confirms for new's refused calls: the
#[sub] verb either runs or refuses without touching disk path.

assert proj has_path == true

#[sub] === Phase 4: argument-shape refusal — zero args ===

#[sub] Call new_doc with no arguments. Expected trace line:
#[sub]
#[sub]   error invoke threw: proj new_doc: expected exactly two
#[sub]   arguments (width and height in pixels)

proj new_doc

#[sub] === Phase 5: argument-shape refusal — one arg ===

#[sub] Same refusal as Phase 4 — args.size() == 1 fails the
#[sub] args.size() != 2 check identically.

proj new_doc 100

#[sub] === Phase 6: argument-shape refusal — three args ===

#[sub] Same refusal as Phases 4 and 5 — args.size() == 3 also
#[sub] fails the args.size() != 2 check. Three different shapes,
#[sub] three identical structured refusals.

proj new_doc 100 200 300

#[sub] === Phase 7: value refusal — zero dimension ===

#[sub] Call new_doc with a zero width. Expected trace line:
#[sub]
#[sub]   error invoke threw: proj new_doc: width and height must
#[sub]   be positive integers
#[sub]
#[sub] The arg parse succeeds (0 is a valid Int literal); the
#[sub] `w <= 0 || h <= 0` check fires. CanvasModel::from_pixels(0,
#[sub] ...) would produce a degenerate canvas with zero viewBox
#[sub] dimensions; the refusal prevents that.

proj new_doc 0 100

#[sub] === Phase 8: value refusal — negative dimension ===

#[sub] Call new_doc with a negative width. Same refusal text as
#[sub] Phase 7; -50 fails the `w <= 0` check.

proj new_doc -50 100

#[sub] === Phase 9: value refusal — string dimension ===

#[sub] Call new_doc with a string in the width slot. The arg_as_int
#[sub] helper returns 0 for non-Int/non-Double ScriptValue kinds
#[sub] (String included); the resulting `w == 0` fails the `w <= 0`
#[sub] check. Same refusal text as Phases 7 and 8 — uniform error
#[sub] voice covers wrong-kind and wrong-range cases under one
#[sub] message.

proj new_doc "wide" 100

#[sub] === Phase 10: post-refusal sanity ===

#[sub] After six refused calls, the project's directory is still
#[sub] unchanged. The refusals are structured early-returns
#[sub] (Scriptable layer for arg shape and value, helper layer for
#[sub] state); no project mutation happened on any of them.

assert proj has_path == true

#[sub] s293 m4 smoke complete. Expected summary line:
#[sub]
#[sub]   8 lines, 3 pass, 1 ok, 6 error
#[sub]
#[sub] - 3 PASS  : has_path == true at Phases 1, 3, 10 (path
#[sub]             unchanged across happy path AND refusals)
#[sub] - 1 ok    : the happy-path new_doc at Phase 2 (the verb
#[sub]             body ran cleanly and returned Null)
#[sub] - 6 error : the six refused new_doc calls at Phases 4-9
#[sub]             (intentional — three argument-shape refusals
#[sub]             and three value refusals)
#[sub] - 1 operator-visual : the `get proj path` echo at Phase 1
#[sub]
#[sub] Tier 4 row stays at 1/~4-5 (no tick — same singleton, sixth
#[sub] verb). Surface widening: `proj` Scriptable verb count goes
#[sub] 5 → 6; context_mask() consumer count goes 6 → 7
#[sub] (registry-promotion clock held at 7/n by design; first
#[sub] verb on this Scriptable since save (s246 m1) to land at
#[sub] the Scripter | TestRunner mask).
#[sub]
#[sub] m5b proj-surface arc remains closed at 5/5 File-menu items.
#[sub] s293 m4 opens a new arc — in-project document-lifecycle
#[sub] verbs — with new_doc as its first verb. Future siblings
#[sub] (close_doc, rename_doc, set_active_doc) land when use
#[sub] cases name the needs.

#[sub] ── Manual exercise for the missing observables ─────────────
#[sub]
#[sub] After the smoke runs, manually verify:
#[sub]
#[sub]   - The new tab in DocTabBar reads "Untitled.svg" (or
#[sub]     Untitled2/3/... if previous runs left tabs). Click it
#[sub]     if not already active.
#[sub]
#[sub]   - The inspector's Size section reads 500 × 500 px and
#[sub]     unit "px".
#[sub]
#[sub]   - The canvas is blank (no objects, no paths).
#[sub]
#[sub]   - The Layers panel shows two layers: "Layer 1" and
#[sub]     "Guides" (the CurvzDocument default-ctor seed).
#[sub]
#[sub]   - tail -20 ~/.local/share/curvz/curvz.log shows the
#[sub]     LOG_INFO line: `script_new_doc: added '<filename>' to
#[sub]     project (500x500)`.
#[sub]
#[sub] These five operator-visuals become assertable observables
#[sub] when the project sprouts inspector queries for canvas
#[sub] dimensions, doc count, active doc filename, and layer
#[sub] names. Banked for future Scriptable-surface widening.
